## Summary

### Contract clauses captured by each test

| Test | Contract clause |
|---|---|
| `doc_test_div_ceil_unsigned_cases` (existing) | Specific input/output points from upstream doc-test |
| **`panics_when_divisor_is_zero`** (new) | **Failure / precondition: `y == 0` ‚áí panic** |
| `postcondition_smallest_q_with_qy_ge_x` (existing) | Postcondition: result is the smallest `q` with `q¬∑y ‚â• x` |
| `postcondition_relation_to_floor_div` (existing) | Postcondition: result equals `‚åäx/y‚åã` when `y ‚à£ x`, else `‚åäx/y‚åã + 1` |
| `agrees_with_source` / `agrees_with_source_at_boundaries` (existing) | Behavioral equivalence to upstream `num_integer::div_ceil` on a small sweep and at boundary values |

### What I added and why

Just one test ‚Äî `panics_when_divisor_is_zero`. The existing suite covered the postcondition and behavioral equivalence well, but the **failure condition** documented on the function (panic when `y == 0`) was not asserted anywhere. Since the failure clause is independent from the value-on-success clause, it earns its own test.

### Properties I considered but did not include

- **`div_ceil(x, 1) == x`** ‚Äî derived from `postcondition_relation_to_floor_div` (when `y == 1`, `x % y == 0`, so the result is `x / 1 == x`).
- **`div_ceil(0, y) == 0` for `y > 0`** ‚Äî derived from the smallest-`q` postcondition (`q = 0` already satisfies `0¬∑y ‚â• 0`).
- **`div_ceil(x, x) == 1` for `x > 0`** ‚Äî derived from the floor-div relation.
- **`div_ceil(x, y) ‚â• x / y`** and **`div_ceil(x, y) ‚â§ x / y + 1`** ‚Äî direct corollaries of the floor-div relation.
- **No-overflow on valid inputs** ‚Äî already implicitly checked by `agrees_with_source_at_boundaries`, which exercises `(u64::MAX, 1)` and other extreme pairs against the reference implementation.
- **Monotonicity in `x` for fixed `y`** ‚Äî derived from being a ceiling function; doesn't add information beyond the smallest-`q` characterisation.

Each of these would create extra proof obligations downstream without pinning down anything the smallest-`q` postcondition and floor-div relation don't already imply.

